{% submission %}

{% submission-part type="problem" %}

Teachers collect large amounts of assessment data through quizzes, benchmarks, assignments, and standardized test preparation, but there is no efficient system for turning that data into targeted instructional intervention.
Identifying learning shortfalls is time-consuming and usually requires teachers to manually analyze assessment results,
identify weak standards, determine recurring misconceptions, group students by instructional need, assign remediation, track intervention completion, and monitor growth over time.
This challenge is especially significant in
alternative school settings, classrooms with rolling enrollment, EOC-tested courses,
mixed-readiness classrooms, and
SPED-inclusive environments.
Most existing educational platforms focus on grade reporting rather than instructional response. Teachers need a practical tool that bridges the gap between assessment data and actionable remediation.
Without an efficient intervention system, 
learning gaps persist, remediation becomes inconsistent, student progress is difficult to track, and teachers spend excessive time managing data instead of delivering instruction.
An app addressing this would help teachers quickly identify learning deficiencies, organize targeted remediation, monitor student mastery, and support data-driven instructional decisions.

{% /submission-part %}

{% submission-part type="proposed-solution" %}

Develop a teacher-centered app that converts assessment data into targeted remediation plans and intervention tracking.
Teachers would upload quiz, benchmark, or formative assessment data, and the app would identify learning gaps by student and standard. The platform would help teachers organize remediation groups, assign interventions, monitor mastery, and track progress over time.
Key features could include standards-based mastery tracking, student intervention profiles,
remediation assignment management,
progress monitoring dashboards, and
reassessment tracking.
The app would reduce the time teachers spend analyzing data while improving consistency, personalization, and effectiveness of remediation efforts, especially in alternative school settings and EOC-tested courses.

{% /submission-part %}

